               <p>SAMUEL SILK. I am a <rs id="t18291203-195-viclabel1008" type="occupation">hatter</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291203-195-victim1223 t18291203-195-viclabel1008"></join>. The prisoner is a <rs id="t18291203-195-deflabel1009" type="occupation">hatter</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291203-195-defend1222 t18291203-195-deflabel1009"></join>, but was not in my employ; I gave him leave, when he had work, to do it at my shop, which is near the Coburg Theatre: on the 16th of October he was there at work - I said I had two hats to take to Mr. Lewis, a publican, and one to another person: the prisoner and I went to Mr.<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182912030071"></xptr>Lewis, and he was not at home - we sat down and had a glass of refreshment, and he said he would take the hats to the bar for safety, as people were coming in; he got up and took them, but did not return - I inquired if they were left, and the landlady said he took them out; he was taken on the 6th of November - these are the hats.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. What were you doing? A. Taking a glass of rum and water, and playing at bagatelle: I could swear to these hats - the linings were out: I did not swear to them before the Magistrate - I believe they are mine.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291203-195-person1224">
                  JOHN 
                  WILCOX
